{"acceptance_criteria":"","actor":"","agent_state":"","assignee":null,"await_id":"","await_type":"","close_reason":"Implemented in 46a0e8b","closed_at":"2026-03-07T03:50:30Z","closed_by_session":"","compacted_at":null,"compacted_at_commit":null,"compaction_level":0,"content_hash":"397258ca8a510f554dbeeb38f758e9162f08f7a5fad21e6668064d7e0b750a89","created_at":"2026-03-05T23:51:25Z","created_by":"Ketan Gangatirkar","crystallizes":0,"defer_until":null,"description":"## Feature\n\nWhen a TypeScript function accepts `number`, shatter can't distinguish integer-intended from float-intended parameters. This leads to noisy float inputs like `intToRoman(410.50190091454465)` where `intToRoman(410)` would be more useful, and misses the interesting edge case that `intToRoman(0.5)` silently returns `\"\"` instead of throwing.\n\n## Design\n\n### Detection\nEarly in exploration, run ~5 float probes alongside their `Math.floor()` equivalents. If `f(x) == f(floor(x))` for ≥N% of probes (configurable threshold, default 80%), classify the parameter as 'integer-treating.'\n\n### Input generation\nFor integer-treating parameters:\n- Generate ~M% integers, ~(100-M)% floats (configurable ratio, default 80/20)\n- The float budget targets boundary values: `0.5`, `-0.1`, `N.999` — values where the fractional part is most likely to change behavior\n\n### Reporting\n- Show `floor()` equivalent as the canonical example: `intToRoman(410)` not `intToRoman(410.50)`\n- If a float input produces a DIFFERENT result from its floor, flag it prominently as a domain validation finding\n- Example: `(0.5) -\u003e \"\" — non-integer input bypasses validation (floor equivalent (0) THROWS Error: out of range)`\n\n### Why not suppress floats entirely\nFloat inputs that diverge from their floor equivalent reveal real bugs (missing input validation). The 20% float budget is where the tool earns its keep — `intToRoman(0.5) -\u003e \"\"` is exactly the kind of surprise shatter exists to surface.\n\n## Configuration\n\nConfigurable via `--set` (see str-TBD for the `--set` system) or YAML config:\n\n- `explore.float_probe.threshold`: confidence threshold for integer classification (default: 0.8)\n- `explore.float_probe.integer_ratio`: fraction of integer inputs when integer-treating detected (default: 0.8)\n- `explore.float_probe.probes`: number of float/floor probe pairs to run (default: 5)\n\nThese are too obscure for top-level CLI flags; they belong in the `--set` / YAML config system.","design":"","due_at":null,"ephemeral":0,"estimated_minutes":null,"event_kind":"","external_ref":null,"hook_bead":"","id":"str-1hnm","is_template":0,"issue_type":"feature","last_activity":null,"metadata":"{}","mol_type":"","notes":"Config system dependency: str-nh7l (--set flag). Complementary static heuristic: str-nfg2.","original_size":null,"owner":"33678+ketang@users.noreply.github.com","payload":"","pinned":0,"priority":2,"quality_score":null,"rig":"","role_bead":"","role_type":"","sender":"","source_repo":"","source_system":"","spec_id":"","status":"closed","target":"","timeout_ns":0,"title":"Float probe: detect integer-treating number parameters via behavioral testing","updated_at":"2026-03-07T03:50:30Z","waiters":"","wisp_type":"","work_type":""}
