{"acceptance_criteria":"","actor":"","agent_state":"","assignee":null,"await_id":"","await_type":"","close_reason":"FrontendCapabilities struct with from_raw() and supports_complex() added to orchestrator.rs. generate_random_value and generate_random_inputs gain caps parameter (Option\u003c\u0026FrontendCapabilities\u003e). Complex type input gen checks capabilities before generating. 410 tests pass, clippy clean.","closed_at":"2026-02-27T05:25:36Z","closed_by_session":"","compacted_at":null,"compacted_at_commit":null,"compaction_level":0,"content_hash":"eea661745636e6b69def9df27b3365103f68d83c937ef37a4ca1452bb1dae128","created_at":"2026-02-27T04:45:44Z","created_by":"Ketan Gangatirkar","crystallizes":0,"defer_until":null,"description":"Add LSP-style capability negotiation for complex types and gate input generation on declared capabilities.\n\n## What\n1. Add FrontendCapabilities struct that parses complex_type:* entries from the handshake capabilities Vec\u003cString\u003e\n2. Update input_gen.rs to accept capabilities and check them before generating complex values\n3. Fall back to generate_unknown() for complex types the frontend didn't declare\n\n## Why\nDifferent frontends support different complex types (TS has Symbol, Go has Rune, neither has the other's). The core must only generate types the frontend can reconstruct. Capability negotiation during handshake (like LSP's initialize) lets each frontend declare what it supports.\n\n## Design\n- FrontendCapabilities { commands: HashSet\u003cString\u003e, complex_types: HashSet\u003cComplexKind\u003e }\n- from_raw(capabilities: \u0026[String]) parses \"complex_type:date\" → ComplexKind::Date\n- supports_complex(kind: ComplexKind) -\u003e bool\n- generate_random_value gains a capabilities parameter (or a context struct)\n- TypeInfo::Complex match arm checks caps.supports_complex(kind) before generating\n- Handshake capability format: \"complex_type:\u003cserde_snake_case_name\u003e\" e.g. \"complex_type:date\", \"complex_type:reg_exp\", \"complex_type:big_int\"\n\n## Files\n- shatter-core/src/protocol.rs or new shatter-core/src/capabilities.rs — FrontendCapabilities\n- shatter-core/src/input_gen.rs — capability-gated generation\n- shatter-core/src/orchestrator.rs — pass capabilities through exploration loop\n\n## Tests\n- FrontendCapabilities::from_raw correctly parses complex_type entries\n- Unknown complex_type strings are silently ignored\n- Non-complex capabilities (\"analyze\", \"execute\") parsed as commands\n- generate_random_value falls back to Unknown for unsupported ComplexKind\n- generate_random_value produces tagged JSON for supported ComplexKind","design":"","due_at":null,"ephemeral":0,"estimated_minutes":null,"event_kind":"","external_ref":null,"hook_bead":"","id":"str-44j","is_template":0,"issue_type":"task","last_activity":null,"metadata":"{}","mol_type":"","notes":"","original_size":null,"owner":"33678+ketang@users.noreply.github.com","payload":"","pinned":0,"priority":2,"quality_score":null,"rig":"","role_bead":"","role_type":"","sender":"","source_repo":"","source_system":"","spec_id":"","status":"closed","target":"","timeout_ns":0,"title":"Core: FrontendCapabilities and capability-gated input generation","updated_at":"2026-02-27T05:25:36Z","waiters":"","wisp_type":"","work_type":""}
{"acceptance_criteria":"","actor":"","agent_state":"","assignee":null,"await_id":"","await_type":"","close_reason":"","closed_at":null,"closed_by_session":"","compacted_at":null,"compacted_at_commit":null,"compaction_level":0,"content_hash":"3196d83681771acf142601466c30754c977a1c31c60a8dac2ff0b2cce25991d4","created_at":"2026-03-02T17:05:02Z","created_by":"Ketan Gangatirkar","crystallizes":0,"defer_until":null,"description":"Functions accepting options objects with function-typed fields (e.g. change-case Options.split) produce only TypeError paths because the engine provides non-function values for callback fields. 11 of 13 change-case functions produce only 'splitFn is not a function' errors.\n\nThis is a constraint solver / input generation enhancement. Design questions:\n- How should the engine detect function-typed fields? (TS type annotations? runtime typeof checks?)\n- What should stub functions return? (undefined? identity? type-appropriate values?)\n- Should stubs be symbolic (enabling path exploration through callbacks) or concrete?\n- How does this interact with the auto-mocking system for external dependencies?\n- Priority relative to other input generation improvements?\n\nBranch coverage is technically 100% but semantic coverage is near zero — the engine finds error branches but not the actual transformation logic.","design":"## Current Architecture\n\n### Type Flow\n1. analyzer.ts convertObjectType() encounters function-typed fields (call signatures) and returns { kind: 'unknown' } (line 704-706)\n2. The core TypeInfo enum has ComplexKind::Closure but input_gen.rs only uses it when the frontend declares support\n3. The TS frontend does NOT declare 'complex_type:closure' in SUPPORTED_CAPABILITIES (handlers.ts line 34-39)\n4. reconstruct.ts has no case for 'closure' — it falls through to the default (log warning, pass through as raw object)\n5. So even if the analyzer emitted Closure, the core would skip it (no capability) and the frontend couldn't reconstruct it\n\n### Result\nObject fields typed as functions get TypeInfo::Unknown → generate_unknown() → random primitive → TypeError at runtime\n\n## Fix Design\n\n### Phase 1: Omit function-typed optional fields (Quick win, highest impact)\n\nThe simplest fix eliminates TypeErrors without needing closure support:\n\n**analyzer.ts convertObjectType()** (line 701-726):\nCurrently at line 703-706:\n```typescript\nconst callSignatures = type.getCallSignatures();\nif (callSignatures.length \u003e 0) {\n  return { kind: 'unknown' };  // entire type treated as unknown if callable\n}\n```\n\nThis is wrong for two reasons:\n1. It returns unknown for the ENTIRE type, not just the callable field\n2. It's at the type level, not the field level — an Options object WITH a callable field still has non-callable fields that should be generated\n\n**The real fix**: In the properties loop (line 713-724), check each PROPERTY for call signatures individually:\n```typescript\nconst fields: [string, TypeInfo][] = properties.map((prop) =\u003e {\n  const propType = checker.getTypeOfSymbol(prop);\n  // Check if this specific property is callable\n  if (propType.getCallSignatures().length \u003e 0) {\n    // Mark as nullable-unknown so the core generates null (omits the field)\n    // when the property is optional\n    const isOptional = (prop.flags \u0026 ts.SymbolFlags.Optional) !== 0;\n    if (isOptional) {\n      return [prop.name, { kind: 'nullable', inner: { kind: 'unknown' } }];\n    }\n    // Required callable field: mark as unknown for now (Phase 2 will improve)\n    return [prop.name, { kind: 'unknown' }];\n  }\n  // ... existing conversion logic\n});\n```\n\nAND remove the early return for callable types at line 703-706, since that's checking the OBJECT type's own call signatures (for function types like () =\u003e void), which is still correct to return unknown for.\n\nWait — the early return IS needed for pure function types (parameters typed as (x: string) =\u003e number). The issue is specifically about OBJECT types that CONTAIN callable fields. The current code is actually correct for pure callable types. The fix should only be in the properties loop.\n\n**input_gen.rs**: For Nullable { inner: Unknown }, generate_nullable already has 30% null chance. But for optional callable fields specifically, we want ~100% null to let the default apply. Two options:\n- Option A: No core change — the 30% null rate means 70% of runs still produce TypeErrors for optional callback fields. Acceptable for Phase 1 since some runs will succeed.\n- Option B: Add a dedicated Callable/Function TypeInfo variant so the core can always generate null. More work.\n\n**Recommended for Phase 1**: Option A (no core change). Even 30% null rate is a massive improvement over 0% success.\n\n### Phase 2: Full closure support (Future)\n\n1. Add 'complex_type:closure' to SUPPORTED_CAPABILITIES\n2. Add closure case to reconstruct.ts:\n   - 'identity' variant → (x) =\u003e x\n   - 'constant' variant → () =\u003e constantValue  \n   - 'thrower' variant → () =\u003e { throw new Error() }\n3. Map callable properties to { kind: 'complex', complex_kind: 'closure' } with metadata containing param/return types\n4. Core already has generate_closure() — it will activate once the frontend declares support\n\n### Required Changes (Phase 1 only)\n\n**analyzer.ts** (~line 713-724):\n- In convertObjectType properties loop, check each property for call signatures\n- If callable + optional → return { kind: 'nullable', inner: { kind: 'unknown' } }\n- If callable + required → return { kind: 'unknown' } (status quo, but now per-field not per-type)\n- Keep the early return at line 703-706 for pure function types (the type itself is callable)\n\n### Test Plan\n- Fixture: function taking { transform?: (s: string) =\u003e string, prefix: string }\n  - Verify transform field gets null, prefix gets a string\n- change-case: verify camelCase produces non-error paths (options.split is optional)\n- Verify pure callable parameters (fn: (x: number) =\u003e number) still get TypeInfo::Unknown","due_at":null,"ephemeral":0,"estimated_minutes":null,"event_kind":"","external_ref":null,"hook_bead":"","id":"str-49k","is_template":0,"issue_type":"feature","last_activity":null,"metadata":"{}","mol_type":"","notes":"","original_size":null,"owner":"33678+ketang@users.noreply.github.com","payload":"","pinned":0,"priority":3,"quality_score":null,"rig":"","role_bead":"","role_type":"","sender":"","source_repo":"","source_system":"","spec_id":"","status":"open","target":"","timeout_ns":0,"title":"Concolic engine generates only error paths for functions with callback-typed options","updated_at":"2026-03-02T19:14:53Z","waiters":"","wisp_type":"","work_type":""}
