{"acceptance_criteria":"","actor":"","agent_state":"","assignee":null,"await_id":"","await_type":"","close_reason":"Generators for all remaining types (Buffer, BitSet, Char, Symbol, Rune, GoByte, Path, UUID, IpAddress) added to input_gen.rs with full dispatch. TS analyzer recognizes Buffer/typed arrays and Symbol via complexKindFromSymbol. Go analyzer recognizes net.IP via complexKindFromNamed. Export formatting handles all types. Reconstruction in both frontends covers these types.","closed_at":"2026-02-27T05:39:55Z","closed_by_session":"","compacted_at":null,"compacted_at_commit":null,"compaction_level":0,"content_hash":"d6043d33a958e8152f504420c177374e91608f4e7561559004d12b57b3316d27","created_at":"2026-02-27T04:47:38Z","created_by":"Ketan Gangatirkar","crystallizes":0,"defer_until":null,"description":"Full support for character-level and symbol text types: generators, analyzer recognition, reconstruction, and tests.\n\n## What\n1. Core generators (input_gen.rs):\n   - generate_char: NUL (0), space (32), 'a', 'Z', '0', '€' (8364), emoji (😀), max Unicode codepoint. Wire format: {\"__complex_type\": \"char\", \"value\": \"€\", \"codepoint\": 8364}\n   - generate_symbol: empty description, short description (\"id\", \"key\"), descriptive name. Wire format: {\"__complex_type\": \"symbol\", \"description\": \"mySymbol\"}\n   - generate_rune: Same as char — Go rune is a Unicode codepoint. Wire format: {\"__complex_type\": \"rune\", \"value\": \"€\", \"codepoint\": 8364}\n   - generate_go_byte: 0, 1, 127, 128, 255, random 0-255. Wire format: {\"__complex_type\": \"go_byte\", \"value\": 65}\n\n2. TS analyzer: Recognize symbol primitive type (ts.TypeFlags.ESSymbol / UniqueESSymbol)\n3. TS reconstruction: Symbol(description)\n4. Go analyzer: Recognize rune (int32 alias) and byte (uint8 alias). These are basic types in Go but have distinct semantics — rune for Unicode, byte for raw bytes.\n5. Go reconstruction: rune(codepoint), byte(value)\n6. Rust: Recognize char type\n\n## Solver\nTier 1 for Char/Rune — comparisons reduce to integer comparisons on codepoint.\nTier 3 for Symbol — JS Symbols are unique and identity-based, not solvable.\n\n## Files\n- shatter-core/src/input_gen.rs\n- shatter-ts/src/analyzer.ts\n- shatter-ts/src/reconstruct.ts\n- shatter-go/protocol/analyzer.go\n- shatter-go/reconstruct/reconstruct.go","design":"","due_at":null,"ephemeral":0,"estimated_minutes":null,"event_kind":"","external_ref":null,"hook_bead":"","id":"str-4j9","is_template":0,"issue_type":"task","last_activity":null,"metadata":"{}","mol_type":"","notes":"","original_size":null,"owner":"33678+ketang@users.noreply.github.com","payload":"","pinned":0,"priority":3,"quality_score":null,"rig":"","role_bead":"","role_type":"","sender":"","source_repo":"","source_system":"","spec_id":"","status":"closed","target":"","timeout_ns":0,"title":"Char/Symbol/Rune text types end-to-end","updated_at":"2026-02-27T05:39:55Z","waiters":"","wisp_type":"","work_type":""}
{"acceptance_criteria":"","actor":"","agent_state":"","assignee":null,"await_id":"","await_type":"","close_reason":"","closed_at":null,"closed_by_session":"","compacted_at":null,"compacted_at_commit":null,"compaction_level":0,"content_hash":"776a89ee4d974279b7119dee1119f2baf90bdbc3e3b15e6bb0f039ce8f5b14c7","created_at":"2026-02-25T21:12:50Z","created_by":"Ketan Gangatirkar","crystallizes":0,"defer_until":null,"description":"Add two complementary sampling modes to shatter scan for exploring a representative subset of functions without running the full codebase.\n\n## Two slicing modes\n\n### --core-sample N% (vertical slice)\nSelects a thin, representative slice through ALL layers of the call graph. Like a geological core sample — every dependency depth is represented proportionally.\n\n  shatter scan \u003cdir\u003e --core-sample 10%             # 10% of functions, from every layer\n  shatter scan \u003cdir\u003e --core-sample 50              # exactly 50 functions, from every layer\n  shatter scan \u003cdir\u003e --core-sample 10% --seed 42   # reproducible selection\n  shatter scan \u003cdir\u003e --core-sample 10% --batch next  # progressive: next disjoint 10%\n\n**Stratification axes** (each batch is independently representative):\n1. Module/directory — proportional representation from each directory subtree\n2. Complexity tier — bucket by branch count (0-1, 2-5, 6-15, 16+), sample proportionally\n3. Dependency depth — sample from each call graph layer (leaves through top-level callers)\n4. Function kind — pure, I/O, constructors, handlers if distinguishable\n\n**Selection algorithm:**\n1. Full discovery + batch analyze (cheap — ~1.3s startup + ~50ms/file)\n2. Classify functions into strata along axes above\n3. Allocate budget proportionally to strata sizes (min 1 per non-empty stratum)\n4. Within each stratum, sort by stable hash of (file_path + function_name + seed), pick first N\n5. Dependency closure: if selected F calls project function G, include G too (doesn't count against budget)\n\n**Determinism:**\n- Default seed = hash(project_name + git HEAD) — same code = same sample\n- --seed for explicit override\n- Stable under additions: new files don't reshuffle existing selections (consistent hashing)\n\n**Progressive batching (--batch):**\n- Functions assigned batch numbers via round-robin within strata\n- Each batch is disjoint and independently representative\n- Later batches inherit behavior maps from earlier batches (better mocking quality)\n- --batch 0 (default), --batch 1, --batch next (auto-detect), --batch 0-2 (run 3 batches)\n\n### --stratum SPEC (horizontal slice)\nExplores functions at specific call graph depths. Layer 0 = leaf functions (no internal deps), higher numbers = more callers. Negative indices count from the top of the call graph: -0 = entry points (not called by anything in scope), -1 = second from top, etc.\n\nUses double-dot range syntax (like git diff) to avoid ambiguity with negative indices.\n\n**Single stratum:**\n  --stratum 0          # leaves only (absolute)\n  --stratum 3          # depth 3 only (absolute)\n  --stratum -0         # top layer (entry points, uncalled within scope)\n  --stratum -1         # second from top\n\n**Ranges (double-dot, both endpoints inclusive):**\n  --stratum 0..3       # depth 0 through 3\n  --stratum -2..-0     # top 3 layers\n  --stratum 2..-1      # absolute depth 2 up to second-from-top (mixed)\n\n**Open-ended ranges:**\n  --stratum 3..        # depth 3 and everything above\n  --stratum ..3        # depth 0 through 3\n  --stratum -2..       # second-from-top through top (same as -2..-0)\n  --stratum ..-1       # everything except the top layer\n\n**Negative index semantics:**\nIf the call graph has max depth D, then:\n  -0 = D (top), -1 = D-1, -2 = D-2, etc.\nThis mirrors Python-style indexing (except -0 is the last, not first, since 'top of call graph' is the natural meaning of -0).\n\n**Composable with --core-sample:**\n  shatter scan \u003cdir\u003e --stratum 0..2 --core-sample 30%   # 30% of layers 0-2\n  shatter scan \u003cdir\u003e --stratum -0 --core-sample 50%     # half the entry points\n\n**Cross-stratum dependency resolution:**\nWhen a function in the selected strata calls a function OUTSIDE the selected strata, the callee is mocked, never pulled in. Mock fidelity depends on prior exploration:\n\n| Scenario | Mock source |\n|---|---|\n| Callee explored in prior run (cached) | Cached behavior map — high fidelity |\n| Callee not yet explored | Type-aware stub — correct types, synthetic values |\n| Callee is in the selected strata | Explored naturally (bottom-up), behavior map available |\n\n**Progressive stratum workflow:**\n  shatter scan \u003cdir\u003e --stratum 0         # explore leaves, build behavior maps\n  # user analyzes\n  shatter scan \u003cdir\u003e --stratum 1         # depth-1 gets real mocks from stratum 0\n  # user analyzes\n  shatter scan \u003cdir\u003e --stratum 2         # even better mocks from strata 0+1\n\nEach layer benefits from behavior maps built by prior layers. Report shows mock quality:\n  Stratum 5: 23 functions explored\n    Mocking: 41 internal calls\n      34 via cached behavior maps (from prior strata)\n      7 via type-aware stubs (callees not yet explored)\n\nWithin a multi-stratum range, functions are always explored bottom-up (lower strata first).\nCycle groups are assigned to the lowest stratum of any member.\n\n## Output\n- Report indicates sampling: 'Explored 47/463 functions (10.2% core sample, strata 0..4)'\n- Lists selected functions, stratum assignments, mock quality per function\n- --dry-run with --core-sample/--stratum shows selection without exploring\n- Cumulative stats across progressive batches\n\n## Edge cases\n- --core-sample budget \u003e total functions: scan everything\n- Empty strata: redistribute budget\n- Dependency closure may push explored count above sample budget — report both\n- --stratum N where N \u003e max depth: error with valid range and suggestion\n- --stratum -N where N \u003e max depth: clamp to 0\n- Resolved range is empty (e.g. 5..3): error\n- Range endpoints equal (e.g. 3..3): single stratum, same as --stratum 3","design":"","due_at":null,"ephemeral":0,"estimated_minutes":null,"event_kind":"","external_ref":null,"hook_bead":"","id":"str-4jx","is_template":0,"issue_type":"feature","last_activity":null,"metadata":"{}","mol_type":"","notes":"","original_size":null,"owner":"33678+ketang@users.noreply.github.com","payload":"","pinned":0,"priority":2,"quality_score":null,"rig":"","role_bead":"","role_type":"","sender":"","source_repo":"","source_system":"","spec_id":"","status":"open","target":"","timeout_ns":0,"title":"Sampling mode: --core-sample and --stratum for representative subset exploration","updated_at":"2026-02-25T21:37:22Z","waiters":"","wisp_type":"","work_type":""}
