{"acceptance_criteria":"","actor":"","agent_state":"","assignee":null,"await_id":"","await_type":"","close_reason":"Implemented probe_values() and generate_probe_inputs() for small-value probing. Covers canonical boundary values per type (0/1/-1 for ints, empty for strings/arrays, null for nullable). Combinatorial inputs capped at configurable budget.","closed_at":"2026-02-26T04:00:52Z","closed_by_session":"","compacted_at":null,"compacted_at_commit":null,"compaction_level":0,"content_hash":"341de55d6e9ebc21b74c3db96fb521f3d0591b1a3c4d06f9de07c6a0d477dabb","created_at":"2026-02-26T03:37:41Z","created_by":"Ketan Gangatirkar","crystallizes":0,"defer_until":null,"description":"Add a lightweight heuristic that probes recursive functions with boundary values to quickly find base-case inputs before doing any symbolic analysis.\n\n## Rationale\n\nBase cases in recursive functions almost always guard against 'empty' or 'minimal' inputs. Probing with a small set of canonical values is cheap and hits base cases in the vast majority of real recursive functions.\n\n## Implementation\n\n1. Define a set of canonical probe values per type: numbers {0, 1, -1}, strings {\"\", \"a\"}, arrays {[], [x]}, booleans {false, true}, null/undefined.\n2. When a function is identified as self-recursive, before symbolic solving, run it with probe values (combinatorially for multi-arg functions, but capped at a small budget like 20 executions).\n3. Executions that terminate without a recursive call are base-case witnesses. Record them as the initial BehaviorMap entries.\n4. This runs as an optional fast pass before the constraint-solving path. If it finds base cases, downstream iterative deepening can start immediately.\n\n## Heuristic: Argument-size monotonicity\n\nAs a refinement, detect which argument decreases in the recursive call (n-1, arr.slice(1), node.left, etc.). If detectable, pick probe values that are 'small' in that dimension specifically. This further increases hit rate.\n\n## Key files\n\n- shatter-core/src/explorer.rs — RandomExplorer or new ProbeExplorer\n- shatter-core/src/behavior.rs — BehaviorMap::from_records()\n\n## Tests\n\n- Probing factorial(n) with {0, 1, -1} finds base cases n=0 and n=1\n- Probing fibonacci(n) with small values finds the base cases\n- Probing a function with array argument using [] finds the empty-list base case\n- Multi-argument recursive function: probing stays within execution budget","design":"","due_at":null,"ephemeral":0,"estimated_minutes":null,"event_kind":"","external_ref":null,"hook_bead":"","id":"str-67y","is_template":0,"issue_type":"task","last_activity":null,"metadata":"{}","mol_type":"","notes":"","original_size":null,"owner":"33678+ketang@users.noreply.github.com","payload":"","pinned":0,"priority":3,"quality_score":null,"rig":"","role_bead":"","role_type":"","sender":"","source_repo":"","source_system":"","spec_id":"","status":"closed","target":"","timeout_ns":0,"title":"Small-value probing for quick base-case discovery","updated_at":"2026-02-26T04:00:52Z","waiters":"","wisp_type":"","work_type":""}
