{"acceptance_criteria":"","actor":"","agent_state":"","assignee":null,"await_id":"","await_type":"","close_reason":"","closed_at":null,"closed_by_session":"","compacted_at":null,"compacted_at_commit":null,"compaction_level":0,"content_hash":"2461a5ec15b00c624128c5a668c14eb8c8fcd377bb3ac82f6490273d31c660a6","created_at":"2026-02-25T18:51:22Z","created_by":"Ketan Gangatirkar","crystallizes":0,"defer_until":null,"description":"A shatter scan \u003cdirectory\u003e command that discovers all functions in a codebase, orders them by dependency depth, and explores them bottom-up using concolic execution. Results from leaf functions become behavior maps used to mock those functions when testing callers. Supports both TS and Go frontends, multi-process parallelism, sensible auto-mocking defaults, and machine-readable output for agent consumption.","design":"","due_at":null,"ephemeral":0,"estimated_minutes":null,"event_kind":"","external_ref":null,"hook_bead":"","id":"str-6aq","is_template":0,"issue_type":"epic","last_activity":null,"metadata":"{}","mol_type":"","notes":"","original_size":null,"owner":"33678+ketang@users.noreply.github.com","payload":"","pinned":0,"priority":1,"quality_score":null,"rig":"","role_bead":"","role_type":"","sender":"","source_repo":"","source_system":"","spec_id":"","status":"open","target":"","timeout_ns":0,"title":"Codebase scan mode: explore all functions in a project","updated_at":"2026-02-25T18:51:22Z","waiters":"","wisp_type":"","work_type":""}
{"acceptance_criteria":"","actor":"","agent_state":"","assignee":null,"await_id":"","await_type":"","close_reason":"","closed_at":null,"closed_by_session":"","compacted_at":null,"compacted_at_commit":null,"compaction_level":0,"content_hash":"69e98bb830842942768061dc3fc9284c198427a32a8083664dacb9f3e2da83cc","created_at":"2026-03-07T23:44:14Z","created_by":"Ketan Gangatirkar","crystallizes":0,"defer_until":null,"description":"The scan orchestrator gives each function a fixed budget (max_iterations_per_function, timeout_per_fn). If a function reaches full coverage or plateaus early, its remaining budget is wasted. Redistribute unused budget to functions that are still discovering new paths.\n\n## Mechanism\n\nTrack per-function exploration outcomes during parallel_scan. When a function terminates early (WorklistExhausted, CoveragePlateau, or full branch coverage), compute its unused budget as (allocated_executions - actual_executions). Feed that surplus into a shared atomic counter. Functions still exploring can request additional budget from the surplus when they exhaust their initial allocation but are still finding new paths.\n\n## Design considerations\n\n- **Surplus accounting**: track by execution count, not wall time — time-based reallocation is harder to reason about with parallel workers.\n- **Claim policy**: a function should only claim surplus if its recent hit rate (new paths / last N executions) exceeds a threshold. Don't let a stalled function consume the entire surplus.\n- **Layer boundaries**: surplus resets at each topological layer boundary. Budget from layer 0 functions should not carry over to layer 1 — the functions are structurally different.\n- **Interaction with str-l22q (stall detection)**: a function that has abandoned all its frontiers should release budget even if its execution count hasn't reached the cap.\n\n## Why this matters\n\nIn practice, simple leaf functions (validators, formatters) often hit full coverage in \u003c10 executions while complex functions with opaque constraints need hundreds. Fixed budgets waste most of the compute on functions that don't need it.\n\nAnalogous to str-l22q (frontier-level abandonment) but operates at the function level within a scan.","design":"","due_at":null,"ephemeral":0,"estimated_minutes":null,"event_kind":"","external_ref":null,"hook_bead":"","id":"str-6aq.1","is_template":0,"issue_type":"feature","last_activity":null,"metadata":"{}","mol_type":"","notes":"","original_size":null,"owner":"33678+ketang@users.noreply.github.com","payload":"","pinned":0,"priority":3,"quality_score":null,"rig":"","role_bead":"","role_type":"","sender":"","source_repo":"","source_system":"","spec_id":"","status":"open","target":"","timeout_ns":0,"title":"Dynamic budget reallocation across functions during scan","updated_at":"2026-03-07T23:44:14Z","waiters":"","wisp_type":"","work_type":""}
{"acceptance_criteria":"","actor":"","agent_state":"","assignee":null,"await_id":"","await_type":"","close_reason":"","closed_at":null,"closed_by_session":"","compacted_at":null,"compacted_at_commit":null,"compaction_level":0,"content_hash":"867c36cf250fb401d927398a0c530c4c76768e32f69d33e0d7204b6cba3808f0","created_at":"2026-03-08T02:07:51Z","created_by":"Ketan Gangatirkar","crystallizes":0,"defer_until":null,"description":"Within a topological layer, the scan orchestrator assigns functions to workers in arbitrary order. When parallelism is limited (fewer workers than functions in a layer), high-yield functions should be explored first so that time-bounded or cancelled scans capture the most valuable results.\n\n## Static signals (available before execution)\n\n- **Branch count**: more branches = higher potential coverage contribution\n- **Caller count** (from call graph): functions with more callers have higher blast radius — a bug in a widely-called utility matters more than in an isolated leaf\n- **Parameter complexity**: struct/array/optional params suggest a richer input space worth exploring early\n- **Dependency depth**: functions calling many other project functions are likely more complex\n\n## Dynamic reordering (during execution)\n\nIf str-6aq.1 (dynamic budget reallocation) is implemented, per-function coverage velocity is already tracked. Use that signal to reorder the remaining work queue: promote functions that are finding new paths, demote functions that plateaued early.\n\n## Composite score\n\nWeighted combination: `score = w1 * branch_count + w2 * caller_count + w3 * param_complexity`. Weights are configurable; sensible defaults chosen empirically. No ML — a simple linear score is sufficient at this scale.\n\n## Why deferred\n\nThe benefit only materializes when parallelism is limited relative to layer size and the scan has a tight time budget. In practice, most layers have few enough functions that all workers stay busy regardless of ordering. Becomes more relevant with farm mode (str-wiza) and total scan timeouts.\n\n## Distinct from\n\n- str-u7mr: prioritizes branch frontiers *within* a single function\n- str-l22q: decides when to *stop* a function, not when to *start*\n- Call graph topological order: determines which *layer*, not priority *within* a layer","design":"","due_at":null,"ephemeral":0,"estimated_minutes":null,"event_kind":"","external_ref":null,"hook_bead":"","id":"str-6aq.2","is_template":0,"issue_type":"feature","last_activity":null,"metadata":"{}","mol_type":"","notes":"","original_size":null,"owner":"33678+ketang@users.noreply.github.com","payload":"","pinned":0,"priority":4,"quality_score":null,"rig":"","role_bead":"","role_type":"","sender":"","source_repo":"","source_system":"","spec_id":"","status":"deferred","target":"","timeout_ns":0,"title":"Intra-layer function prioritization by expected yield","updated_at":"2026-03-08T02:07:51Z","waiters":"","wisp_type":"","work_type":""}
