{"acceptance_criteria":"","actor":"","agent_state":"","assignee":null,"await_id":"","await_type":"","close_reason":"Duplicate of str-qsr3","closed_at":"2026-03-06T21:17:43Z","closed_by_session":"","compacted_at":null,"compacted_at_commit":null,"compaction_level":0,"content_hash":"4a516a3471d213bd1a8ae544122a1deb8f306c4fddc0433edb17a4954246846a","created_at":"2026-03-06T18:31:14Z","created_by":"Ketan Gangatirkar","crystallizes":0,"defer_until":null,"description":"After the discovery phase (find distinct behaviors), run a separate refinement phase that binary-searches between known inputs on opposite sides of each branch to find precise transition points.\n\nKey design:\n- SEPARATE budget from discovery (e.g. --refine-budget N per boundary, distinct from --max-executions)\n- Discovery benefits from breadth (spread inputs across the domain)\n- Refinement benefits from focus (narrow in on a known boundary)\n- Mixing them in the same loop with the same budget means one steals from the other\n\nAlgorithm per boundary:\n1. Take two inputs: one triggering behavior A, one triggering behavior B\n2. Interpolate/mutate between them using shrink_candidates\n3. Re-execute, track which behavior each result triggers\n4. Converge on the precise transition point\n\nOutput:\n- Precise boundary descriptions in behavioral spec\n- Minimal inputs at each transition point\n- Higher-quality seeds for the interesting pool\n\nShatter should prioritize finding precise boundaries — this is a distinct phase, not mixed into discovery.","design":"","due_at":null,"ephemeral":0,"estimated_minutes":null,"event_kind":"","external_ref":null,"hook_bead":"","id":"str-6dtq","is_template":0,"issue_type":"feature","last_activity":null,"metadata":"{}","mol_type":"","notes":"Epic: str-08r7 (Formal methods and property-based verification)","original_size":null,"owner":"33678+ketang@users.noreply.github.com","payload":"","pinned":0,"priority":2,"quality_score":null,"rig":"","role_bead":"","role_type":"","sender