{"acceptance_criteria":"","actor":"","agent_state":"","assignee":null,"await_id":"","await_type":"","close_reason":"Closed","closed_at":"2026-03-06T02:41:40Z","closed_by_session":"","compacted_at":null,"compacted_at_commit":null,"compaction_level":0,"content_hash":"235b0c2496787ad3fa354cd8329b773601047ef45fba1dfe79346e7c5c86208a","created_at":"2026-03-05T23:33:04Z","created_by":"Ketan Gangatirkar","crystallizes":0,"defer_until":null,"description":"## Problem\n\nThe scan report lumps all skipped functions into a single 'Skipped functions:' section with no visual distinction between:\n\n1. **Expected skips** — opaque parameter types (`net.Socket`, `stream.Readable`), fingerprint cache hits, checkpoint resumes\n2. **Actual errors** — exploration errors, deserialization failures, frontend crashes, timeouts\n\nIn a real codebase, many functions will have opaque types (DB connections, sockets, file handles). These are normal and expected — they're not actionable failures. But they currently look identical to real errors in the report.\n\n## Current output\n\n```\nSkipped functions:\n  handleRequest: param \"socket\" has opaque type net.Socket\n  processStream: param \"input\" has opaque type stream.Readable\n  authenticate: error: exploration error: unexpected response from frontend\n```\n\n## Expected behavior\n\nThe report should visually separate these categories. For example:\n\n```\nSkipped (opaque types, 2):\n  handleRequest: param \"socket\" has opaque type net.Socket\n  processStream: param \"input\" has opaque type stream.Readable\n\nErrors (1):\n  authenticate: exploration error: unexpected response from frontend\n```\n\nOr at minimum, prefix reasons with a category tag so automated tools (and AI agents reviewing output) can distinguish them.\n\n## Impact\n\nAI agents running the walkthrough or reviewing scan output can't distinguish normal opaque-type skips from real bugs. This was a contributing factor in pipeline bugs going undetected — the agent sees 'Skipped functions' and either ignores all of them (missing real errors) or flags all of them (drowning signal in noise).","design":"","due_at":null,"ephemeral":0,"estimated_minutes":null,"event_kind":"","external_ref":null,"hook_bead":"","id":"str-73pl","is_template":0,"issue_type":"feature","last_activity":null,"metadata":"{}","mol_type":"","notes":"","original_size":null,"owner":"33678+ketang@users.noreply.github.com","payload":"","pinned":0,"priority":2,"quality_score":null,"rig":"","role_bead":"","role_type":"","sender":"","source_repo":"","source_system":"","spec_id":"","status":"closed","target":"","timeout_ns":0,"title":"Scan report mixes expected skips (opaque types, cache hits) with actual errors","updated_at":"2026-03-06T02:41:40Z","waiters":"","wisp_type":"","work_type":""}
